  "prompt": "Can a country run without president?",
  "response": "Yes, a country can operate without a president, although it depends on the specific government structure and constitution of that country. Some countries do not have a presidential system and instead have other forms of leadership and governance.\n\nFor example:\n1. **Parliamentary Systems:** In many parliamentary democracies, the head of state is typically a monarch (as in the United Kingdom, Sweden, or Japan) or a ceremonial president (as in Germany or India), while the head of government is a prime minister who holds executive powers.\n\n2. **Monarchies:** In absolute monarchies such as Saudi Arabia or Brunei, the monarch holds significant power.\n\n3. **Non-Presidential Republics:** Some countries have other forms of governance where a president may exist but hold only ceremonial roles, with real executive power vested in a prime minister or other officials. \n\n4. **Temporary Solutions:** In cases of political crisis, a country may operate temporarily without a president, relying on vice presidents, interim leaders, or other governmental structures to maintain stability and continuity.\n\nIf the position of president becomes vacant due to resignation, impeachment, or other reasons, constitutional provisions usually exist to fill the role temporarily through mechanisms like succession (vice president, speaker of the house, etc.) until a new president is elected or appointed.\n\nOverall, the specific structure and rules of governance vary significantly from country to country.",
